            <lg type="quatrain" met="-+(4/3/4/3)" rhyme="abcb" org="uniform" sample="complete" part="N">
                <l n="1" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-++--+">
                    <seg>West<sb/></seg>
                    <seg>ron wynde </seg>
                    <seg>when wyll </seg>
                    <seg>thow <rhyme label="a">blow</rhyme></seg>
                </l><l n="2" met="-+-+-+" real="-+++-+">
                    <seg>The smalle </seg>
                    <seg>rayne downe </seg>
                    <seg>can <rhyme label="b">rayne</rhyme></seg>
                </l><l n="3" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+--+-+-+">
                    <seg>Chryst yf </seg>
                    <seg>my love </seg>
                    <seg>wer in </seg>
                    <seg>my <rhyme label="c">armes</rhyme></seg>
                </l><l n="4" met="-+-+-+" real="-+--+-+">
                    <seg>And I </seg>
                    <seg>yn my bed </seg>
                    <seg>a<sb/><rhyme label="b">gayne</rhyme></seg>
                    <note anchored="true">
                        Hauntingly suggestive, yet fulfillingly self-sufficient, this pensive brief lament owes some of its amplitude to the changes it rings on the common-measure stanza.  No two lines scan the same; nor is any line straight iambic.  On this miniature scale the poem's one spondee, in line 2, lets the "small rain" seem to have seeped into everything, while the way slack pairs (u u) migrate to a different position in each of the other lines helps instill into the whole lyric a surprisingly vivid sense of observant alertness.
                    </note>
                 </l></lg></body></text></TEI>